10. Don't wear black dress shirts

Especially in dressy materials like a very smooth poplin. If you want to wear a black button-up, try a casual material like a black denim Western shirt or needlecord. Or better yet, a knit like George here. It's more tasteful.

If you enjoyed these looks, it's perhaps worth pointing out that they appeared on television nearly thirty years ago. The fact that George Costanza remains a style icon is a testament to the timelessness of these guidelines. Ignore them at your peril. https://t.co/LbeU30GMSd

9. Check for balance

When trying on a jacket, check to see if the jacket hangs evenly from front to back. Tailors call this "balance." The front can be lower or level with the back, but it should never be higher than the back. This can be a challenge for barrel-chested guys.

Lots of misinformation in the replies. First, consider whether you need bespoke or made-to-measure. These are two different things. Bespoke means that the tailor is, at least in theory, drafting your pattern from scratch and then producing the garment through a series of three fittings. Made to measure means the garment is produced by adjusting a block pattern, made straight to finish, and then adjusted through a single fitting.

Some body types will require bespoke; others may be ok with made-to-measure. Many will be OK with ready-to-wear. Determining what you need will help you figure out your options.

There are no bespoke tailors in this area. Everyone who uses a bespoke tailor relies on traveling tailors who visit the Bay Area once every three to four months for trunk shows. Since a bespoke suit requires at least two, if not three, fittings and an initial meeting, this puts production well beyond your timeline.

All the options listed in these replies are made to measure, not bespoke. This can be fine, depending on how well you fit into the block pattern. To determine this, ask if they have a try-on suit. This can function as an "interim fitting." The more you have to change to the block pattern, the more risk you take. The less you change, the better. All of these MTM operations rely on other factories, often located in other countries, which means production time may still fall outside of your requirements. 

Much depends on your height, chest size, and waist size. As well as your budget. Given the very tight timeline, I would contact all the MTM programs and ask if they have try-on suits and order some ready-to-wear suits to try out. But which suits to order again depends on your body shape.

IMO, it's misguided to think about colors like this bc fashion is more akin to language than an absolute science. To think about how to combine colors, you should first think about the cultural language you want to express and how colors are used in that language. Examples:

I've mentioned many times that our rules around classic men's tailoring largely derive from the cultural practices of British elites during the late 19th century and all of the 20th century. During that period, London business dress consisted of a dark suit worn with a white shirt, dark tie, and black oxfords. Brown shoes were reserved for country sport. Hence the phrase, "no brown in town." In this sense, a navy suit worn with black oxfords is always classic. 

Similar combinations and traditions can be found elsewhere. A classic Italian look is a navy suit with black Gucci horsebit loafers; a classic American look is a navy suit with black tassel loafers. Both of these remain classic because their cultural touchpoints continue to hold cultural capital. 

Similarly, a black knit tie is one of the most classic ties you can wear. It goes with suits and sport coat of any color (including navy suits, brass button blazers, and plain navy sport coats). The black silk knit was perhaps most famously worn by the literary version of James Bond, who Iam Flemming described as wearing a dark suit, a clean white shirt, and a “thin, black silk knitted tie.” It’s also heavily associated with other mid-century icons, such as Black jazz musicians and members of the Rat Pack. Again, the combination continues to be good because these cultural reference points continue to hold cultural capital. 

A black leather double rider (a type of motorcycle jacket with an asymmetric closure) looks great with blue jeans because it was the standard rebel-rocker look for much of the post-war period. Think of Marlon Brando striking a rebel pose in The Wild One or the enduring image of The Ramones. This will never not look good because of what such a uniform conveys. 

Any kind of rugged black boot—combat boots, work boots, Doc Martens, etc.—will look great with blue jeans because of the history of punk, workwear, and militaria. If you're wearing an olive field jacket with blue jeans, you'll always look good with black boots because it evokes stories about rugged men that many people find appealing. 

By contrast, you shouldn't wear a black suit jacket with blue jeans because that will make you look like you spilled something on your black suit pants and had to change out of them. Or black leather pants with a blue sport coat because that makes no cultural sense. Understanding how to combine colors relies more on understanding cultural language than it is about memorizing these pithy rules, such as "blue and green should never be seen without another color in between."

@JacAshby Raw denim jeans and olive military jackets derive their history from work. Jeans from mining; olive military jackets for war. Even neckerchiefs were something worn by cowboys and Appalachian coal miners. IMO, black derbies/ boots work here since they are also work shoes

The key: you want to avoid the sartorial mullet (dressy up top; too casual down bottom). Don't wear suit jackets with jeans, especially with white dress shirts and ties. https://t.co/tGXoZe20i6

A navy jacket looks great with jeans so long as it can pass as a sport coat. You want to avoid looking like you threw on a suit jacket. A jacket will look more "suit-y" depending on a few variables, principally the fabric. A smooth, silky worsted wool with a slight sheen will be very a suit. By contrast, a textured, matte fabric will be more obviously a sport coat. 

There are some other things, such as whether a jacket has a swelled edge, brass buttons, or patch pockets. All these elements can help make a navy jacket look more obviously like a sport coat. Below are some examples of navy jackets that look at home with denim. 

When you are shopping for clothes, a designer will have made these design decisions for you. So you just have to ask the sales associate: is this a sport coat or a suit jacket? If you are commissioning custom clothes, a tailor can recommend the right fabric and styling decisions.

There's no way to test this because there's no counterfactual. 

We have one outcome: she landed a job at the NYT to create content. Clearly, they hired her partly because of her education. But could she have gotten the same job with fewer degrees?

There are two ways to test this. You could go back in time and remove one or two degrees—or have her get a totally different degree (PhD)—and see if she still lands the same job. 

Or you could have a pool of people with similar jobs (although drawing such comparisons will be tough) and compare their qualifications. 

Whether you, as an outsider who is not an expert in this field, think that 3 terminal MAs are redundant has little relevance to the outcome (her landing a job), as you are not the person hiring her.

John Groth was a war correspondent, an illustrator, and Esquire's first Art Director. He covered six conflicts, including the Vietnam War, and was one of the first American correspondents in Paris after the city's liberation. 

He said: "It is only at war that I feel complete. There, you meet all sorts of men—farmers, mechanics, college professors. It rains on them and it rains on you. The shells burst in the air, and you are there, too."

One of his tailors, Paul Winston, once told me that Groth was quite fond of smoking tobacco. One day, while giving a lecture at a university, he absent-mindedly put his not-yet-extinguished pipe into his jacket's breast pocket. Midway through the lecture, his jacket caught fire. After that, Groth had all of his bespoke sport coats and suit jackets made with a special fireproof pipe pocket.

@jacob_pearlman shirts are less complicated than tailored jackets. if you do online mtm, you will have an easier time getting a good fit in shirts than jackets.

This is also why cheap and/ or online made-to-measure companies (for things like suits, not shirts) can be risky. Cheap companies often rely on trendy blocks (read: very slim, short jackets that don't fit anyone). Online MTM companies also don't have fitters or sample garments.

Don't assume that MTM is automatically better than RTW. Think of it like the editors of that 1918 tailoring book: getting the right fit is like figuring out how to solve a problem. Some need bespoke or MTM; others are fine with RTW. Also good RTW is better than bad MTM/ bespoke https://t.co/sF53MZwHv8
